      "The earliest known greeting card dates back to around 1415, when a French duke sent a card to his wife from prison. Romantic? Absolutely. Practical? Well, it worked — we're still talking about it 600 years later.",
      "But greeting cards really took off in the 1800s when the penny post system made it affordable to send mail in England. Suddenly, you didn't need to be a duke to send someone a card. By the 1850s, mass-produced Christmas cards were a thing, and the greeting card industry was born.",
      "For about 150 years, not much changed. Cards got fancier — pop-ups, musical cards (who remembers those birthday cards that wouldn't stop playing music?), scented cards. But the format was the same: buy a card, write something, put it in an envelope, mail it.",
      "Then came the internet, and everything shifted. E-cards exploded in the early 2000s — remember those websites where you'd pick an animated card and type the recipient's email? They felt revolutionary at the time. But they also felt... impersonal. Like you couldn't even be bothered to go to a store.",
      "The smartphone era changed things again. WhatsApp and Instagram became the default way people share wishes. But instead of thoughtful messages, we got an avalanche of forwarded images. A step backward, honestly.",
      "Now we're seeing a new wave — interactive digital greetings. Not just static images, but experiences. Animated gift boxes that open. Festival-specific interactions like lighting a Diwali lamp or cracking an Easter egg. The greeting isn't just a message anymore; it's a moment.",
      "What most people don't fully appreciate is how dominant the physical greeting card industry became in the 20th century. By the 1950s in the US, companies like Hallmark and American Greetings had turned card-giving into an industrial ritual. Cards were designed, mass-produced, and marketed at specific emotional beats — birthdays, sympathy, anniversaries, get well soon, thank you, congratulations. The idea that you should buy a card from a store pre-dated mass production, but these companies turned occasional thoughtfulness into a consumer expectation. If you didn't send a card, society had a word for that: negligent.",
      "That commercial standardization is precisely what hollowed out the feeling of cards even as it preserved the habit. When everyone buys from the same ten templates at the same pharmacy counter, the gesture becomes obligatory rather than personal. You're not saying 'I thought of you specifically.' You're saying 'I fulfilled the cultural requirement of acknowledging this occasion.' Those are two very different things dressed in the same envelope.",
      "The internet didn't just change the delivery mechanism. It exposed that gap. When email made it possible for anyone to create a basic digital card, the limitations of the store-bought version became visible by contrast. Personalization was possible again — not pen-on-paper physical, but typed-by-your-own-hands, chosen-specifically-for-this-person personal. That was a shift worth noticing.",
      "What the current generation of interactive digital tools does that even early e-cards couldn't is return active participation to the sender. Choosing a design with intention. Typing someone's name. Selecting a message that fits THEM rather than a generic demographic. Opening a digital gift box on the receiving end. These are small acts, but they are choices — and choices are how care becomes visible. The effort is modest, but it is yours, and that is what people feel when it lands.",
      "What's interesting is that the core purpose hasn't changed in 600 years. Whether it's a duke writing from a prison cell or someone typing their name into WishSpark, the intent is the same — telling someone \"I'm thinking of you.\" The medium changes, but the meaning doesn't.",
